1
00:00:01,963 --> 00:00:03,925
We were supposed to play tennis
in Karuizawa,

2
00:00:04,009 --> 00:00:05,261
but the rain canceled it,

3
00:00:05,345 --> 00:00:07,975
so we ended up going bowling instead.

4
00:00:08,393 --> 00:00:12,067
So? Who is it?
This person you want me to meet.

5
00:00:12,150 --> 00:00:15,782
Oh, that would be the person
who waited four whole hours

6
00:00:15,907 --> 00:00:17,577
on a tennis court in a downpour.

7
00:00:17,703 --> 00:00:21,210
He's changing out of his wet clothes,
he should be here any minute.

8
00:00:21,293 --> 00:00:23,966
Quit dragging it out and just tell me.

9
00:00:24,049 --> 00:00:26,929
I rode my bike all the way here
in this rain, you know.

10
00:00:28,766 --> 00:00:30,019
Huh?

11
00:00:31,939 --> 00:00:33,192
What are you?

12
00:00:37,200 --> 00:00:38,578
Jeet Kune Do.

13
00:00:38,661 --> 00:00:40,248
He dodged it? Ha.

14
00:00:47,637 --> 00:00:50,268
Not bad. I'll knock you flat.

15
00:00:50,351 --> 00:00:53,024
No, you've got it wrong, Sera.
Huh?

16
00:00:53,107 --> 00:00:56,990
That's him. The person Sonoko
wanted you to meet.

17
00:00:57,073 --> 00:00:58,326
Huh?

18
00:00:58,618 --> 00:01:00,914
Over Sonoko, Sera and Kyogoku

19
00:01:00,998 --> 00:01:03,669
ended up trading a few punches,

20
00:01:03,753 --> 00:01:07,636
but in the end we were enjoying bowling
with the junior high teachers we'd just met.

21
00:01:09,389 --> 00:01:13,064
But the PE teacher,
who was supposed to be asleep in the car, vanished,

22
00:01:13,606 --> 00:01:15,527
and we all set out to look for him...

23
00:01:18,366 --> 00:01:22,457
Aaah! Kyaaa!
Wh-what happened?

24
00:01:23,543 --> 00:01:25,797
Th-the bathroom lock was open,

25
00:01:25,880 --> 00:01:29,179
so I opened it, and... and inside...

26
00:01:38,322 --> 00:01:40,076
The sun's blazing,
undaunted by the heat,

27
00:01:40,159 --> 00:01:41,954
a slick and stylish deduction show.

28
00:01:42,038 --> 00:01:45,795
Sera's suspicious behavior over email?
Clear Makoto Kyogoku's name.

29
00:01:45,879 --> 00:01:47,424
Seeing through the one and only truth,

30
00:01:47,507 --> 00:01:49,094
Looks like a kid,
mind of an adult.

31
00:01:49,177 --> 00:01:51,473
his name is Detective Conan!

32
00:01:53,609 --> 00:01:58,994
♪~

33
00:03:27,130 --> 00:03:33,142
~♪

34
00:03:35,136 --> 00:03:38,936
"Makoto Kyogoku, A Suspect? (Part 2)"

35
00:03:41,867 --> 00:03:44,664
Huh? No mistake, it was drowning?

36
00:03:44,998 --> 00:03:46,293
Really?

37
00:03:46,376 --> 00:03:48,297
Yes. There was water

38
00:03:48,422 --> 00:03:51,428
in the victim's airway,
according to the medical examiner.

39
00:03:52,180 --> 00:03:56,146
But even if he was knocked out
with a stun gun,

40
00:03:56,271 --> 00:04:00,821
drowning a man that big
without even tying him up...

41
00:04:00,905 --> 00:04:03,118
wouldn't that take two or three people?

42
00:04:03,202 --> 00:04:09,255
True. Well, a karate master
could manage it alone, though.

43
00:04:09,756 --> 00:04:12,303
What? You're still
suspecting Makoto?

44
00:04:12,386 --> 00:04:13,639
N-not really.

45
00:04:14,098 --> 00:04:19,692
Oh, and there's also a report of
cord-like compression marks on the victim's lower abdomen.

46
00:04:19,776 --> 00:04:21,988
The lower abdomen?
Yes.

47
00:04:22,073 --> 00:04:24,827
The marks didn't reach up to the waist,

48
00:04:25,371 --> 00:04:29,128
so the culprit may have carried the body
by grabbing the belt.

49
00:04:29,462 --> 00:04:31,006
I see.

50
00:04:31,091 --> 00:04:35,182
In that case, the culprit must have
considerable physical strength.

51
00:04:35,266 --> 00:04:38,480
Someone like, say, a karate master.

52
00:04:38,563 --> 00:04:40,359
Ugh... gh... uh...

53
00:04:40,859 --> 00:04:44,409
I-it's just an example. Just an example.

54
00:04:45,202 --> 00:04:49,961
Come to think of it, the man who was killed
said something about going through a lot.

55
00:04:50,087 --> 00:04:52,258
What happened?
Ah.

56
00:04:52,883 --> 00:04:55,180
Mr. Tanba
- Masaki Sunami (29) junior high school science teacher
- Monna Michiko (30) junior high school mathematics teacher

57
00:04:55,264 --> 00:04:57,643
had promised to marry my sister,

57
00:04:57,935 --> 00:05:00,399
but his parents were against it.

58
00:05:00,482 --> 00:05:04,991
The truth is, he had a fiancée
their parents had arranged for him.

59
00:05:05,743 --> 00:05:08,123
When they found out,
it was a shock for them both,

60
00:05:08,206 --> 00:05:11,671
and for a while it seemed
they were going to elope.

61
00:05:11,755 --> 00:05:16,431
But in the end, only my sister
threw herself into the sea, drowning herself.

62
00:05:16,514 --> 00:05:17,933
Hmm.

63
00:05:18,018 --> 00:05:20,522
You were the one she talked to
about eloping?

64
00:05:20,939 --> 00:05:24,072
Yes. I got an email from my sister.

65
00:05:24,155 --> 00:05:26,951
"The two of us are setting off now," it said.

66
00:05:27,244 --> 00:05:30,167
That email came to my phone too.

67
00:05:30,250 --> 00:05:33,632
She and I were classmates
and best friends.

68
00:05:33,715 --> 00:05:35,094
It was after that, wasn't it?

69
00:05:35,177 --> 00:05:39,227
That Mr. Tanba started getting violent
whenever he drank.

70
00:05:39,310 --> 00:05:41,648
Yes. So while we were bowling,

71
00:05:41,731 --> 00:05:44,654
he must have woken up,

72
00:05:44,737 --> 00:05:46,991
gotten into a fight with someone, and...

73
00:05:47,451 --> 00:05:51,751
Hey, do you teachers
come to this bowling alley a lot?

74
00:05:51,835 --> 00:05:56,261
Yes. Because the woman who passed away
loved bowling.

75
00:05:56,344 --> 00:05:59,016
Come to think of it,
it was raining last time we came too.

76
00:05:59,434 --> 00:06:00,811
Hmm.

77
00:06:01,396 --> 00:06:04,944
Inspector Yamamura,
from the trash can next to the bathroom,

78
00:06:05,028 --> 00:06:08,410
we found a wet towel
and four strange empty cans.

79
00:06:08,493 --> 00:06:10,038
Empty cans?

80
00:06:10,122 --> 00:06:13,712
Yes. All four had
scorch marks around the openings.

81
00:06:14,255 --> 00:06:16,968
Did someone use them as ashtrays?

82
00:06:17,052 --> 00:06:18,805
Hmm, no, but...

83
00:06:18,889 --> 00:06:21,811
There's a smell of kerosene inside.
Kerosene?

84
00:06:23,690 --> 00:06:25,903
Ah, wait, Conan.

85
00:06:28,805 --> 00:06:30,224
- Sunday Bowl Parking Lot.

86
00:06:32,750 --> 00:06:34,879
Excuse me, forensics?
Hmm?

87
00:06:35,923 --> 00:06:38,637
Could you check something for me?
On that shelf up there...

88
00:06:38,720 --> 00:06:41,851
No, no, no.
Kids, go play over there.

89
00:06:41,935 --> 00:06:44,190
But Mr. Mouri told me

90
00:06:44,273 --> 00:06:46,361
that behind the spare toilet paper,

91
00:06:46,444 --> 00:06:48,740
there might be something.
Huh?

92
00:06:49,116 --> 00:06:51,496
Sheesh, fine, fine.

93
00:06:51,579 --> 00:06:54,126
If Sleeping Kogoro asked for it...

94
00:06:55,754 --> 00:06:58,468
Hm? A scorch mark on the ceiling?

95
00:06:58,927 --> 00:07:01,516
Hey, take a picture. A picture.
A-ah, yes.

96
00:07:02,059 --> 00:07:03,603
Just as I thought.

97
00:07:04,855 --> 00:07:09,365
This explains why the lower part
of the bathroom wall was oddly wet.

98
00:07:10,200 --> 00:07:13,415
No doubt about it.
The culprit is that person.

99
00:07:14,709 --> 00:07:18,758
"It seems he's reached the truth too,

100
00:07:19,260 --> 00:07:21,681
but whether it matches my own deduction,

101
00:07:21,764 --> 00:07:26,149
lately I've been feeling
a little short on confidence."

102
00:07:28,570 --> 00:07:30,324
(phone vibrating)

103
00:07:30,407 --> 00:07:32,536
Oh, that was a fast reply.

104
00:07:33,455 --> 00:07:35,334
"Who is 'he'?" huh.

105
00:07:36,127 --> 00:07:38,048
Yeah, figured he'd ask that.

106
00:07:42,097 --> 00:07:43,350
(camera shutter)

107
00:07:50,530 --> 00:07:53,411
(phone vibrating)

108
00:07:53,495 --> 00:07:56,292
Oh, here it comes. Huh?

109
00:07:58,630 --> 00:08:01,928
"If it's him, there's no problem," he says.

110
00:08:04,809 --> 00:08:06,729
It's a fight. A fight.

111
00:08:07,314 --> 00:08:09,860
The victim, who was sleeping
drunk in the car,

112
00:08:09,944 --> 00:08:14,870
woke up, went to some bar for another drink,
got into a fight with someone,

113
00:08:14,954 --> 00:08:18,001
got dragged off somewhere,
and was killed.

114
00:08:18,545 --> 00:08:23,346
But when Mr. Mouri's group
went around the bars looking for the victim,

115
00:08:23,430 --> 00:08:26,436
nobody said they'd seen him, right?

116
00:08:26,769 --> 00:08:29,942
Hmph. They were just
playing dumb, no doubt.

117
00:08:30,819 --> 00:08:33,867
If word got out that
customers had a fight at the bar,

118
00:08:33,950 --> 00:08:36,414
the place's reputation would suffer.

119
00:08:36,497 --> 00:08:38,209
But why would the culprit

120
00:08:38,293 --> 00:08:40,338
have a stun gun on them?

121
00:08:40,881 --> 00:08:45,265
And we don't even know
where or how he was drowned.

122
00:08:45,348 --> 00:08:49,148
On top of that, why the body was
left all the way over

123
00:08:49,231 --> 00:08:53,823
in the portable toilet in the parking lot
where the victim's car was, makes no sense.

124
00:08:53,907 --> 00:08:56,162
How should I know.

125
00:08:56,746 --> 00:08:59,835
Anyway, the victim, Mr. Tanba,

126
00:08:59,919 --> 00:09:04,053
was taken by this Mr. Masaki
to the car in the parking lot

127
00:09:04,136 --> 00:09:09,104
to sleep it off until he sobered up.
About an hour later,

128
00:09:09,188 --> 00:09:12,903
before Ms. Monna went to the parking lot
to check on him,

129
00:09:12,986 --> 00:09:14,865
he woke up and slipped out of the car.

130
00:09:15,575 --> 00:09:18,498
When we heard Mr. Tanba had gone missing

131
00:09:18,581 --> 00:09:23,925
and went around the bars looking for him,
he got into a quarrel with somebody somewhere,

132
00:09:24,009 --> 00:09:29,353
was drowned, and before we got back
to the parking lot again,

133
00:09:29,436 --> 00:09:33,152
he was stuffed into the parking lot's toilet.
No doubt about it.

134
00:09:33,778 --> 00:09:39,164
Well, this karate guy here,
who was napping that whole time

135
00:09:39,248 --> 00:09:42,671
in a car in the same parking lot,
isn't entirely free of suspicion either,

136
00:09:43,131 --> 00:09:47,431
but considering the culprit used a stun gun,
he's in the clear.

137
00:09:47,931 --> 00:09:50,854
So go around the local bars right now

138
00:09:50,937 --> 00:09:53,109
and do some proper questioning.

139
00:09:53,192 --> 00:09:54,737
Ah... right.

140
00:09:55,196 --> 00:09:58,369
Inspector Yamamura,
the experiment is ready, apparently.

141
00:09:58,453 --> 00:09:59,830
Huh? Experiment?

142
00:10:00,332 --> 00:10:01,667
Ah... yes.

143
00:10:01,751 --> 00:10:05,926
Detective Mouri said it was necessary
to solve the case,

144
00:10:06,427 --> 00:10:09,266
and forensics said you'd approved it, Inspector.

145
00:10:09,350 --> 00:10:11,896
Huh? What's that supposed to mean?

146
00:10:11,979 --> 00:10:14,026
I don't remember
saying anything like that.

147
00:10:14,109 --> 00:10:18,952
Huh? B-but forensics said
the boy was the one...

148
00:10:19,328 --> 00:10:20,997
Ah, anyway, let's go check.

149
00:10:21,082 --> 00:10:22,668
I love experiments!

150
00:10:23,044 --> 00:10:27,177
Has a first-grade brat
ever even done an experiment?

151
00:10:27,260 --> 00:10:29,640
Well, maybe at the professor's house.

152
00:10:30,141 --> 00:10:33,314
Anyway, let's go
and hear what's going on.

153
00:10:33,398 --> 00:10:34,650
Right.

154
00:10:39,618 --> 00:10:41,789
"If it's him, there's no problem"?

155
00:10:42,541 --> 00:10:43,835
Why?

156
00:10:43,918 --> 00:10:45,755
Why does he know?

157
00:10:47,134 --> 00:10:49,138
My brother knows about this kid...

158
00:11:00,027 --> 00:11:02,324
Hey, hey, what's all this?

159
00:11:02,991 --> 00:11:05,580
The area around the toilet
is completely flooded.

160
00:11:05,664 --> 00:11:08,503
Ah, but Detective Mouri

161
00:11:08,586 --> 00:11:10,924
told us to do it this way.
Huh?

162
00:11:11,467 --> 00:11:16,184
He said to stuff a towel in the drain
to dam up the rainwater and collect it.

163
00:11:16,644 --> 00:11:17,896
I see.

164
00:11:17,980 --> 00:11:21,529
They said this area's tilted
from land subsidence,

165
00:11:21,612 --> 00:11:24,785
so the rain that was falling earlier
all pooled up.

166
00:11:26,079 --> 00:11:30,087
But doesn't this
ruin a crucial crime scene?

167
00:11:30,170 --> 00:11:34,680
If you mean the toilet where the body was,
we moved it elsewhere and we're investigating it.

168
00:11:34,763 --> 00:11:37,811
Huh?
This is a different portable toilet.

169
00:11:38,229 --> 00:11:39,773
We heard Detective Mouri

170
00:11:39,857 --> 00:11:42,821
instructed us to do this too...

171
00:11:42,904 --> 00:11:45,702
Hm?
Like I said, I never...

172
00:11:46,329 --> 00:11:48,666
(tranquilizer dart)
Ow! Hanyon.

173
00:11:49,418 --> 00:11:50,754
Hanyon.

174
00:11:51,797 --> 00:11:55,012
Ah, Dad,
there's water pooled right there.

175
00:11:55,513 --> 00:11:58,436
So my pants get wet,

176
00:11:58,519 --> 00:12:00,899
that kind of thing doesn't matter,
I'm telling you.

177
00:12:01,525 --> 00:12:03,905
Not if I can prove this trick.

178
00:12:04,281 --> 00:12:06,535
Huh?
A t-trick?

179
00:12:06,952 --> 00:12:11,670
Don't tell me he was drowned
with this pooled rainwater?

180
00:12:12,004 --> 00:12:17,474
But collecting this much rainwater
would take a fair amount of time,

181
00:12:17,557 --> 00:12:20,397
and even if he was knocked out
with a stun gun,

182
00:12:20,480 --> 00:12:24,446
forcibly drowning a grown man
without binding his hands and feet,

183
00:12:24,530 --> 00:12:27,828
in a place like this,
means the culprit, after all,

184
00:12:27,911 --> 00:12:31,627
must be someone with
considerable physical strength.

185
00:12:31,710 --> 00:12:34,758
That's why I keep saying
Makoto isn't the one.

186
00:12:34,842 --> 00:12:36,136
Right, Makoto?

187
00:12:36,846 --> 00:12:39,601
Ah, Makoto.
Ah, he ran off!

188
00:12:39,685 --> 00:12:41,272
Leave him be.
Huh?

189
00:12:41,814 --> 00:12:43,568
He probably just went to the bathroom.

190
00:12:44,068 --> 00:12:45,989
Besides, he's got nothing to do with this.

191
00:12:46,072 --> 00:12:47,325
Huh? But...

192
00:12:47,784 --> 00:12:51,417
Because this trick
requires no physical strength.

193
00:12:52,001 --> 00:12:54,548
The culprit locked the victim in the toilet

194
00:12:54,631 --> 00:12:58,222
and drowned him
without laying a hand on him.

195
00:12:59,098 --> 00:13:01,479
Just like magic.

196
00:13:04,318 --> 00:13:05,695
Magic.

197
00:13:06,572 --> 00:13:08,409
Seeing is believing.

198
00:13:09,076 --> 00:13:10,747
Let's try it for real.

199
00:13:11,290 --> 00:13:15,172
Whether a person can really drown
inside a toilet.

200
00:13:15,548 --> 00:13:17,302
Of course, Inspector Yamamura,

201
00:13:17,385 --> 00:13:18,971
you're the test subject.

202
00:13:19,389 --> 00:13:21,727
Huh? M-me?

203
00:13:22,395 --> 00:13:23,689
It's fine.

204
00:13:23,773 --> 00:13:26,152
I had them prepare portable oxygen.

205
00:13:26,654 --> 00:13:30,202
...wait, isn't this
an oxygen tank or something?

206
00:13:30,286 --> 00:13:32,541
Hey, tomboy.
Hm?

207
00:13:32,832 --> 00:13:34,670
Help me set up the trick.

208
00:13:35,463 --> 00:13:38,219
You've figured out this trick too, right?

209
00:13:38,302 --> 00:13:39,930
Yeah, more or less.

210
00:13:40,557 --> 00:13:43,437
First, put the victim in the toilet.

211
00:13:44,565 --> 00:13:48,406
Seal the vent on the back of the toilet
with packing tape.

212
00:13:49,198 --> 00:13:54,418
Next, prepare four cans filled with kerosene,
each with a cloth wick in the mouth.

213
00:13:54,793 --> 00:13:59,219
Light those cloths,
line the cans up on the toilet's shelf,

214
00:14:00,012 --> 00:14:04,396
then just close the door
and seal the gaps with packing tape.

215
00:14:05,857 --> 00:14:08,404
So how does that drown someone?

216
00:14:08,487 --> 00:14:10,157
Just watch.

217
00:14:21,764 --> 00:14:24,143
Ugh... sheesh.

218
00:14:25,020 --> 00:14:27,859
The water only comes up
to above my ankles.

219
00:14:28,736 --> 00:14:31,533
As if a person could drown in this.

220
00:14:32,327 --> 00:14:37,127
Still, it's sure getting hot in...
ah, they went out.

221
00:14:37,253 --> 00:14:39,800
(water rushing)
Wh-whaaa?

222
00:14:40,301 --> 00:14:41,553
(banging)

223
00:14:42,179 --> 00:14:45,018
Wh-what?
What on earth is happening inside?

224
00:14:52,575 --> 00:14:54,913
Now, behold.

225
00:14:58,796 --> 00:15:02,220
(heavy breathing)

226
00:15:02,303 --> 00:15:04,599
Haa, haa, ugh...
You okay?

227
00:15:05,058 --> 00:15:07,313
Ugh, what a thing

228
00:15:07,397 --> 00:15:09,108
to put me through, Mr. Mouri.

229
00:15:09,191 --> 00:15:12,282
I nearly drowned to death in there!

230
00:15:12,741 --> 00:15:16,290
But why was there
so much water inside the toilet?

231
00:15:16,373 --> 00:15:19,211
Because the pressure inside
the toilet dropped.

232
00:15:19,671 --> 00:15:23,094
Look, haven't you seen this
in a science experiment?

233
00:15:23,178 --> 00:15:27,479
You stand a lit candle
in a deep dish filled with water,

234
00:15:27,562 --> 00:15:32,697
put a beaker over it,
the flame goes out, and in no time the water

235
00:15:32,781 --> 00:15:35,995
gets sucked up into the beaker.

236
00:15:36,078 --> 00:15:37,248
It's the same thing.

237
00:15:38,041 --> 00:15:41,965
On the shelf of the sealed toilet,
the cans were burning,

238
00:15:42,090 --> 00:15:47,017
the air was heated and expanded,
the oxygen level inside the toilet dropped,

239
00:15:47,100 --> 00:15:49,314
and when the flames went out,
the air cooled and contracted.

240
00:15:49,940 --> 00:15:52,152
By that amount,
through the vent under the door,

241
00:15:52,237 --> 00:15:55,785
it sucked in a huge volume
of the pooled rainwater.

242
00:15:56,578 --> 00:15:58,206
This explanation is correct, isn't it...

243
00:15:59,960 --> 00:16:01,296
science teacher,

244
00:16:02,005 --> 00:16:03,717
Sunami Masaki?

245
00:16:05,095 --> 00:16:09,646
First, on your way to taking
the drunk Mr. Tanba to the car,

246
00:16:09,729 --> 00:16:12,402
you lured him into the portable toilet.

247
00:16:12,485 --> 00:16:15,491
Probably telling him
you'd forgotten the car keys,

248
00:16:15,575 --> 00:16:19,332
so you'd wait out the rain
inside the toilet, or something like that.

249
00:16:20,293 --> 00:16:24,217
And once he was inside,
you immediately knocked him out with the stun gun,

250
00:16:24,301 --> 00:16:28,809
passed a cord through the back of his belt,
tied it to the joint of the toilet seat lid,

251
00:16:28,893 --> 00:16:30,855
so Mr. Tanba couldn't stand up,

252
00:16:31,732 --> 00:16:34,863
placed four cans of kerosene
on the toilet shelf,

253
00:16:35,698 --> 00:16:39,372
put a padlock on the door,
and stuck up an "out of order" sign.

254
00:16:40,165 --> 00:16:44,424
After that, you sealed the vent
on the back of the toilet with packing tape,

255
00:16:44,507 --> 00:16:47,221
stuffed a towel
into the parking lot's drain

256
00:16:47,305 --> 00:16:50,645
to let the rainwater pool,
and the groundwork was complete.

257
00:16:51,062 --> 00:16:55,738
You lied to Ms. Monna,
saying he'd fallen asleep in the car,

258
00:16:55,821 --> 00:16:58,953
waited for the rainwater to collect,
and after a while,

259
00:16:59,036 --> 00:17:00,915
when the worry-prone Ms. Monna

260
00:17:00,998 --> 00:17:04,756
went to check on Mr. Tanba,
it all went according to plan.

261
00:17:05,215 --> 00:17:09,098
Well, if she hadn't suggested it herself,
you'd have

262
00:17:09,181 --> 00:17:13,357
invited her along to go check on him.

263
00:17:13,440 --> 00:17:18,575
Just as you expected, she came to report
that Mr. Tanba wasn't in the car,

264
00:17:18,659 --> 00:17:21,163
and we decided to search the parking lot.

265
00:17:21,581 --> 00:17:25,213
You confirmed that
the rainwater had pooled enough,

266
00:17:25,297 --> 00:17:29,222
peeled the sign off the toilet,
removed the padlock,

267
00:17:29,305 --> 00:17:31,768
lit the cans you'd placed on the shelf,

268
00:17:31,852 --> 00:17:34,189
and sealed the door
with packing tape.

269
00:17:34,649 --> 00:17:38,615
After that, just like the experiment,
the rainwater got sucked into the toilet,

270
00:17:38,741 --> 00:17:43,417
and around the time Mr. Tanba drowned,
you, together with Ms. Monna,

271
00:17:43,500 --> 00:17:46,465
were going around the bars
looking for Mr. Tanba,

272
00:17:46,548 --> 00:17:49,094
building an alibi, the goal in sight.

273
00:17:49,929 --> 00:17:54,606
Then you returned to the parking lot again,
took the towel out of the drain,

274
00:17:54,689 --> 00:17:58,989
drained the pooled rainwater,
peeled off all the packing tape,

275
00:17:59,073 --> 00:18:03,457
threw the cans that had burned on the shelf
into the trash, cut the cord on the belt,

276
00:18:04,083 --> 00:18:07,130
and to hide the fact that
water had pooled inside the toilet,

277
00:18:07,214 --> 00:18:11,681
you fitted the fresh toilet paper
from the shelf onto the holder,

278
00:18:12,140 --> 00:18:14,813
and then, as if you'd
just discovered the body,

279
00:18:14,896 --> 00:18:17,067
let out a scream.

280
00:18:17,443 --> 00:18:21,535
The key to this crime
was how to speed up the discovery of the body.

281
00:18:21,868 --> 00:18:26,210
If the discovery was delayed
and the estimated time of death widened,

282
00:18:26,545 --> 00:18:28,507
the alibi would be wasted.

283
00:18:29,133 --> 00:18:34,017
That's why the culprit can only be you,
the one who found the body first.

284
00:18:34,644 --> 00:18:38,777
You're also the only one who
could make the time to pool the rainwater.

285
00:18:40,155 --> 00:18:44,789
And by now, forensics is finding
the packing tape with your fingerprints on it

286
00:18:44,873 --> 00:18:46,835
in the toilet tank.

287
00:18:47,378 --> 00:18:51,177
Since it wasn't in the trash,
you must have flushed it down the toilet,

288
00:18:51,261 --> 00:18:54,350
and packing tape is hard to peel off
without bare hands.

289
00:18:54,809 --> 00:18:58,734
...that's right, isn't it?
Sleeping Kogoro.

290
00:18:58,817 --> 00:19:00,529
Ah... yeah.

291
00:19:00,613 --> 00:19:02,867
This is some kind of mistake.

292
00:19:03,201 --> 00:19:05,289
I mean... I mean, Sunami

293
00:19:05,372 --> 00:19:08,420
had no reason at all
to kill Mr. Tanba...

294
00:19:08,503 --> 00:19:11,050
I did.
Huh?

295
00:19:14,432 --> 00:19:18,232
A perfectly good motive...
my best friend was left to die

296
00:19:18,690 --> 00:19:20,319
by that man.

297
00:19:21,655 --> 00:19:25,287
Y-your best friend...
don't tell me, my sister?

298
00:19:25,579 --> 00:19:26,748
Yes.

299
00:19:26,831 --> 00:19:30,798
Your sister,
who'd promised to marry that man.

300
00:19:30,881 --> 00:19:36,309
Huh? But my sister
threw herself off a cliff by the coast,

301
00:19:36,768 --> 00:19:38,647
and there was a proper suicide note,

302
00:19:38,730 --> 00:19:41,778
And before that,
you got an email from her, didn't you?

303
00:19:42,028 --> 00:19:44,325
"The two of us are setting off now."

304
00:19:44,617 --> 00:19:45,828
Huh? Y-yes.

305
00:19:46,246 --> 00:19:49,042
That wasn't an email about eloping.

306
00:19:49,126 --> 00:19:52,842
It was a message about the two of them departing to the next world together. A suicide pact.
- "From now on, the two of us will set out on a journey."

307
00:19:53,175 --> 00:19:54,429
Huh?

308
00:19:54,804 --> 00:19:59,522
And yet... and yet,
that man suddenly grew afraid of dying,

309
00:19:59,605 --> 00:20:03,195
and without even saving her as she drowned,
he walked away from that cliff.

310
00:20:03,572 --> 00:20:06,661
Is that... is that true?
Yes.

311
00:20:07,663 --> 00:20:11,463
While Drunk that man blabbed all about it.

312
00:20:12,423 --> 00:20:16,681
Crying that he was
a hopeless, spineless coward.

313
00:20:19,395 --> 00:20:25,198
Well, even a man like that
was someone my best friend loved enough to die for.

314
00:20:27,286 --> 00:20:30,124
So I sent him to her.

315
00:20:30,626 --> 00:20:34,007
Into the water, where she was waiting.

316
00:20:34,717 --> 00:20:40,729
♪~

317
00:21:48,990 --> 00:21:54,252
~♪

318
00:21:54,919 --> 00:21:59,094
Huh? You went off to look for the culprit?
Yes.

319
00:21:59,428 --> 00:22:03,562
B-but you didn't even know
who the culprit was, right?

320
00:22:03,645 --> 00:22:05,189
So how?

321
00:22:05,649 --> 00:22:10,074
Well, the culprit seemed to be
quite a formidable one,

322
00:22:10,157 --> 00:22:13,623
so I figured I'd know them on sight,
from their killing intent.

323
00:22:13,707 --> 00:22:16,003
Huh?
Huh?

324
00:22:16,086 --> 00:22:17,881
And if you got lucky,

325
00:22:17,965 --> 00:22:21,138
you were hoping to
trade a few blows, weren't you?

326
00:22:21,222 --> 00:22:22,474
(yawn)

327
00:22:22,850 --> 00:22:25,772
W-well, that too, a little.

328
00:22:26,274 --> 00:22:29,864
You were planning to fight!
Hahahaha.

329
00:22:30,532 --> 00:22:33,705
Man, even so,
that's Sleeping Kogoro for you.

330
00:22:33,788 --> 00:22:37,296
Solving it so brilliantly like that!

331
00:22:37,379 --> 00:22:39,508
Hm? W-well, yeah.

332
00:22:40,134 --> 00:22:41,846
That's me, the real deal.

333
00:22:42,180 --> 00:22:43,391
But, but, that experiment...

334
00:22:43,391 --> 00:22:44,352
But, but, that experiment...
(Ha, that hack... his usual way of talking is totally back.)

335
00:22:44,352 --> 00:22:44,477
(Ha, that hack... his usual way of talking is totally back.)

336
00:22:44,477 --> 00:22:46,104
If you'd told me beforehand...
(Ha, that hack... his usual way of talking is totally back.)

337
00:22:46,104 --> 00:22:48,150
(Ha, that hack... his usual way of talking is totally back.)

338
00:22:48,568 --> 00:22:50,196
But, well, the good parts...

339
00:22:50,280 --> 00:22:53,495
he went and stole every single one of them.

340
00:22:53,953 --> 00:22:55,791
Ah, that reminds me, Dad,

341
00:22:56,334 --> 00:22:59,005
you'd better change your pants soon
or you'll catch a cold.

342
00:22:59,089 --> 00:23:00,676
Huh?
I mean...

343
00:23:00,759 --> 00:23:03,556
you were sitting in a puddle
doing your deduction earlier.

344
00:23:03,640 --> 00:23:06,186
Huh? Ah!

345
00:23:06,270 --> 00:23:09,192
Wh-what is this? I'm soaked!

346
00:23:09,276 --> 00:23:12,156
But, mister, you were the one who said

347
00:23:12,241 --> 00:23:14,537
you didn't care if your pants got wet.

348
00:23:14,620 --> 00:23:16,916
Did I? I said that?

349
00:23:17,292 --> 00:23:20,799
You did, you did.
It was super cool!

350
00:23:20,882 --> 00:23:23,555
Super cool?
Enough already, hurry up and change.
(phone notification)
Hm?

351
00:23:23,555 --> 00:23:23,596
(phone notification)
Hm?

352
00:23:23,888 --> 00:23:26,227
Email? It's from my brother.

353
00:23:27,019 --> 00:23:31,571
Ah, so that's what it was.

354
00:23:34,910 --> 00:23:36,456
Hm. A postscript?

355
00:23:36,539 --> 00:23:37,791
(tapping)

356
00:23:38,293 --> 00:23:40,295
"Have you already met the magician?" (Kaito Kid)

357
00:23:47,936 --> 00:23:49,273
Yeah, you bet.

358
00:23:52,069 --> 00:23:55,577
I heard. Kid's coming again, right?

359
00:23:56,412 --> 00:23:57,873
Kid.

360
00:23:59,835 --> 00:24:04,135
Kyogoku and Kaito Kid
are going to face off?

361
00:24:04,637 --> 00:24:06,766
Well, you'll find out when you get there.

362
00:24:07,739 --> 00:24:09,366
"Let's have a fair fight - Kaito Kid"

363
00:24:11,651 --> 00:24:13,195
I'll protect it, no matter what.

364
00:24:13,696 --> 00:24:15,617
I stake this fist on it.

365
00:24:15,617 --> 00:24:20,886
Next Conan:
"Thief Kid vs. Makoto Kyogoku (Part 1)"

366
00:24:36,386 --> 00:24:38,586
Next Conan's Hint:

367
00:24:38,586 --> 00:24:41,286
"Unexpected Security System"

368
00:24:41,286 --> 00:24:42,858
There will be no broadcast next week.

369
00:24:43,108 --> 00:24:43,984
Let's drink!

370
00:24:44,193 --> 00:24:45,110
Let's do some work for once.
